Yes, basically, if you create a sascfg_personal.py file and put it in any directory that's already in the pythonpath (I don't think adding a location to the search path is hacky, actually, I think that's the whole point of having a search path; I have to add things to search paths on windows and linux for things to work plenty), and you just have one definition for each access method with only the 'trigger' key, and you set SAS_config_options = {'lock_down': False}, then you can do what you showed above.

This can be your entire sascfg_personal.py:
```
SAS_config_names = ['IOM', 'STDIO', 'SSH']
SAS_config_options = {'lock_down': False}
IOM = {'java'      : 'x'}
STDIO={'saspath': 'x'}
SSH={'ssh'     : 'x'}
```
Then you can build your SAS_Environment as you have and submit the SASsession like you have and it should work today. The only thing you need to do is have that sascfg_personal.py with the 'stub' definitions in a directory in the python search path. Of course, you can put any common keys in the definitions if you don't want to generate all of the them all the time, but if you are generating them all, all you need is a non-zero length value for each of those keys (I just used 'x'). Those keys are what trigger the specific access methods which will then parse your dictionary with the values overriding values.

Thoughts?
